assemblage.p:
Consider an infinite series of the form T(x) = \sum_{k=0}^{\infty} c_k (x-a)^k, where a is any real number.  Let r_n(x) = \frac{c_{n+1} (x-a)^{n+1}}{c_n (x-a)^n} and 

  r(x) = \lim_{n \to \infty} r_n(x) = \lim_{n \to \infty} \frac{c_{n+1} (x-a)^{n+1}}{c_n (x-a)^n}
.
Then,





      for any real number x such that |r(x)| \lt 1, the series T(x) converges;






      for any real number x such that |r(x)| \gt 1, the series T(x) does not converge;






      and for any x such that |r(x)| = 1, the series T(x) may or may not converge.

statement.p:
Explain why the Taylor series centered at a = 0 for f(x) = \sin(x) is 

  T_f(x) = \sum_{k=0}^{\infty} (-1)^{k} \frac{1}{(2k+1)!}x^{2k+1}

and find the interval of x-values for which this Taylor series converges.  Investigate whether or not the Taylor series converges to f(x) = \sin(x).
